<Content>Great service at the New Otani My husband and I stayed at the New Otani for 5 nights on our belated honeymoon in March 2007. We booked a standard Tower room on expedia and were quite happy with the accommodations. The New Otani is an old money, elegant, and respected institution.The hotel is located in Akasaka-Mitsuke, close to 2 subway stops and several different subway lines. We found lots of very reasonably priced restaurants serving many different kinds of Japanese food within easy walking distance of the hotel. We particularly liked Jangara Ramen, which serves the prime minister's favorite ramen.The New Otani is massive. We found it convenient to have many services at our disposal. For example, on a couple occasions we bought groceries at the am/pm and/or the supermarket in the hotel and had a picnic in our room. We bought shinkansen train tickets to Kyoto from the travel agency. (This was after we had gone to Tokyo Station and were unable to figure out where to buy the tickets.) We used the international ATM at the post office to withdraw yen. And it was very easy for us to get to and from Narita using the airport limousine bus.Service at the New Otani, like everywhere in Japan, is really good. The staff were extremely polite and gracious. For example, after we stayed at the New Otani for 4 nights, we stored some of our luggage there while we visited Kyoto for 2 nights. We returned to the New Otani for our last night in Japan before our flight back to the States. When we returned to the New Otani, we found that the bellhop had already delivered our bags to our new room.We splurged on the breakfast buffet at the Garden Court one morning and it was quite good. It included some unusual items, like salad and french fries. The garden is gorgeous. The buffet does not include eggs, pancakes, or waffles. 
