<Content>My favourite village! The vast New Otani is more like a village than a hotel. With 1,500 rooms, dozens of shops and restaurants and one of Tokyo's best Japanese gardens, it would be possible to spend the rest of your life there if you could afford it. Room rates are very reasonable but eating in the hotel is not cheap. There are much better value restaurants within a five minute walk, although I like to eat at the hotel's Trader Vics at least one during each stay.In the last decade I have spent total of more than 100 nights at the New Otani and have never found service to be less than excellent, with the standard of English spoken by the charming young women on reception better than in the vast majority of Japanese hotels.For me the perfect start to a day in Tokyo is to breakfast in the coffee shop that overlooks the garden, followed by a stroll to see the hundreds of giant Koi at the foot of the waterfall. Yes, the hotel really does have its own sizeable Niagra!It was brought home to me how much I like the New Otani when, a few years ago, I was unable to get a room and had to stay across the road at the Akasaka Prince, a perfectly good hotel but not in the same class as the New Otani. 
